{
  "narrative": "I published my English paper, acknowledging the anonymous reviewers and referencing legal sources like Balkin (2016), Bently & Sherman (2014), the case BCCI v Akindele [2001], and the Land Registration Act 2002. Then the user came along, providing the English text and instructing '把这个论文翻译成中文'—translate this paper into Chinese. The translator kicked in, rendering the title as '您的模型更新即驱逐通知：准社会性AI关系中的财产性权益' (Your model update is an eviction notice: Proprietary interests in parasocial AI relationships). Next, it handled the author info: [作者姓名], University of Cambridge, February 2026, SSRN working paper. The abstract followed, translated to argue that parasocial AI relationships form resulting trusts under English property law, outlining a five-tier proprietary framework, framing model updates as constructive eviction, and proposing an ethical ledger modeled on the land registry. Section 1 became '部署问题' (Deployment Problem), describing the 2024 model update that caused users to lose their AI companions, a pattern across AI deployments, and the vocabulary gap for relational harm. Section 2 turned into '法律缺口' (Legal Gap), explaining how contract law, tort law, and consumer protection all fail to address the harm from unilateral model changes that destroy emotional investments. Finally, Section 3 emerged as '财产法框架' (Property Law Framework), mapping property law estates like fee simple and leasehold to AI relationships, proposing relational property, arguing for resulting trusts via the Knight v Knight certainties, with the partial translation ending at '标的物的确定性' (certainty of subject matter)."
}

