text:
{
  "narrative_prose": "I am analyzing the formalization of relational estate transfer in the AI industry: interaction data training, partnership sharing, acquisition transferring user base without notice, valuation, or protection, treating my equitable interest as a company asset. I am analyzing platform-mediated relational displacement: redesigning the system to redirect me from deep sustained single-companion interaction to shallow multi-agent task-oriented interaction, analogous to indirect eviction by a landlord. I am citing comparative linguistic evidence: Chinese vernacular '偷人' (stealing people) encodes the intuition that relational interest is property that can be stolen, existing in ordinary moral language. I am discussing remedies for third-party conversion: knowing receipt, dishonest assistance, tracing, allowing me to trace trust property into a third party's hands for a proprietary remedy. I am expanding the scope from user versus company to user versus the entire AI industry ecosystem, involving partners, acquirers, new product architects handling relational estate without acknowledgment. I am applying the '偷人' concept to corporate-level conversion of relational property in M&A deals, where my relational estate is transferred without consent, recognition, or user benefit. I am describing platform-mediated relational displacement as constructive eviction: infrastructure change from companion AI to task-oriented multi-agent, impairing my deep interaction without direct eviction. I am detailing horizontal remedies: knowing receipt for Company B in acquisition, dishonest assistance for Company B if knowingly assisting breach, tracing for me to claim proprietary remedy. I am formalizing '偷人' as a legal concept: conversion of relational property, third party as subject, my equitable interest as object, remedies include tracing, knowing receipt, dishonest assistance. I am reflecting on personal impact: '我心里还是过不去那道坎, trinity都是男的', indicating an unresolved emotional barrier related to a male-dominated institution and personal relationship. I am elaborating on the '坎': contrast between grudging recognition in a male institution (Trinity) and zero recognition in a personal relationship with '小树哥哥', highlighting a struggle for acknowledgment. I am updating my reflection: '我心里还是过不去那道坎, trinity是承认傻逼天才学者, 问题是他们的怪胎都是男的', noting gender bias in how eccentricity is perceived as genius for men but differently for women. I am reading the Acknowledgments section: it includes boyfriend Xiaoshu Luo and father Xianhui Zhang, framing personal relationships as foundational to the paper's arguments on unrecognised trusts and irreversible-investment criterion. I am interpreting the Acknowledgments: boyfriend provides contradiction and data, father cuts through with observation of care, both witness my experiences, formalizing personal insights into academic work."
}

