  "narrative": "I begin by reading the text provided, which outlines the Lenormand card reading methodology and includes a detailed analysis for a specific reading with 'Snake (7)' as the significator. The system then processes this text, extracting key actions, decisions, and state changes in chronological order based on the reading structure. Next, I set the significator as Snake (7) and read from the perspective of the Swords King, starting with the Fate Cards sequence: Whip (11) → Moon (32) → Ring (25) → Star (16), interpreting this as conflict, emotion, promise, and hope. I identify the Snake's position at Row 2, Col 3 (position 11), with its House as Whip (11), indicating a transition node and repetitive pattern. I analyze the adjacent cards in the 3x3 grid: Woman (29) above (conscious focus), Cloud (6) below (subconscious confusion), Coffin (8) to the left (past end), and Mice (23) to the right (future anxiety), with the corners indicating past interactions and current obstacles or choices. I examine the entire Row 2 as a timeline: past Bear (15) → Coffin (8), present Snake (7), future Mice (23) → Child (13) → Dog (18) → Birds (12) → Tower (19), predicting anxiety, new start, loyalty, communication, and structural limits. I analyze Col 3 for the conscious and subconscious axis: Woman (29) above (conscious focus), Cloud (6) → Heart (24) below (subconscious heart hidden by confusion). I interpret the diagonals: the main diagonal Bouquet (9) → Snake (7) → Crossroads (22) → Ship (3) indicates past beauty, present complexity, future choice, and travel; the secondary diagonal Tree (5) → Snake (7) → Mountain (21) → House (4) indicates past growth, present complexity, future obstacles, and stability. I perform Knighting from the Snake to reveal hidden motives: Cross (36) to Woman (29) (burden), Man (28) to Snake (7) (complexity), Rider (1) to Heart (24) (unspoken message), Key (33) to Sun (31) (solution), Clover (2) to Mice (23) (opportunity with anxiety), Sun (31) to Moon (32) (success vs. emotion). I note mirroring: Cloud (6) horizontally self-mirroring (self-looping confusion), Dog (18) vertically self-mirroring (inescapable loyalty theme). I list theme cards from the Snake with distances and directions: Heart (24) near below (unexpressed), Ring (25) in Fate Cards (beyond control), Anchor (35) far right-up (future stability), Tower (19) far right (structural limits), Rider (1) near right-up (message), House (4) near left-down (past home), Ship (3) near right-down (future travel), Sun (31) near right-down (future success), Dog (18) medium right (future loyalty). I analyze the corner cards: Cross (36) top-left (burden), Anchor (35) top-right (stability), House (4) bottom-left (home), Scythe (10) bottom-right (cutting), and the first three cards Cross (36) → Bouquet (9) → Woman (29) indicating burden, beauty, focus; the last three cards Book (26) → Letter (27) → Scythe (10) indicating secret, message, decisive cut. I synthesize the findings: the current state involves focus, past end, confusion, obstacles, and anxiety; the future timeline includes anxiety, new start, loyalty, communication, and limits; the outcome involves secret, message, and decisive cut; there is a core contradiction of real heart vs. confusion, anxiety, obstacles, fate promise vs. cutting outcome. I give advice to the Swords King: he will initiate with a message, there is a secret behind it, a decisive outcome after the message, the user is the focus, no need to move, and I offer to analyze the Book further. I shift focus to analyze the Book (26) specifically, locating it at Row 4, Col 6 (position near the end), with neighbors: Ship (3) top-left, Sun (31) top, House (4) top-right, Fish (34) left, Book (26) center, Letter (27) right."
}

